<Layout title="Idempotency: The Secret to Reliable API Design — Rupadana">
  <article class="reveal">
    <span class="tag">System Design</span>
    <h1>Idempotency: The Secret to Reliable API Design</h1>
    <div class="meta">Why doing the same thing twice shouldn't break your system.</div>

    <div class="card article-content">
      <p>
        In the world of distributed systems, networks are unreliable. Requests fail, timeouts happen, 
        and clients often retry. But what happens if a client retries a "Charge Credit Card" request 
        because they didn't get a response, even though the first request actually succeeded? 
        Without <strong>Idempotency</strong>, you might just charge them twice.
      </p>

      <div class="callout">
        An API is <strong>idempotent</strong> if making the same request multiple times has the 
        same effect as making it once. It’s the difference between a system that is fragile 
        and one that is production-ready.
      </div>

      <h2>HTTP Methods and Idempotency</h2>
      <p>
        The HTTP specification defines certain methods as naturally idempotent:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>GET:</strong> Fetching data multiple times doesn't change anything.</li>
        <li><strong>PUT:</strong> Replacing a resource with the same data multiple times leaves the resource in the same state.</li>
        <li><strong>DELETE:</strong> Deleting something that is already gone results in the same final state (it's gone).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        However, <strong>POST</strong> is notably <em>not</em> idempotent. Every time you POST to a 
        collection, you typically create a new record. This is where most idempotency bugs live.
      </p>

      <h2>The "At-Least-Once" Delivery Problem</h2>
      <p>
        In distributed systems, we often deal with "at-least-once" delivery. This means a message 
        might be delivered once, or it might be delivered five times due to network retries. 
        If your backend isn't idempotent, these retries will cause data corruption or duplicate side effects.
      </p>

      <h2>How to Implement Idempotency</h2>
      <p>
        The most common way to handle idempotency for non-idempotent methods (like POST) is by 
        using <strong>Idempotency Keys</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>1. The Client Generates a Key</h3>
      <p>
        The client generates a unique identifier (usually a UUID) for a specific operation and 
        sends it in a header, for example: <code>Idempotency-Key: fd6817b7-2245...</code>.
      </p>

      <h3>2. The Server Checks the Key</h3>
      <p>
        When the server receives the request, it checks its database (or a fast cache like Redis) 
        to see if it has already processed a request with that specific key.
      </p>

      <h3>3. Return the Cached Response</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>If the key exists:</strong> The server skips the processing and returns the <em>exact same response</em> it sent the first time.</li>
        <li><strong>If the key doesn't exist:</strong> The server processes the request, saves the result along with the key, and then returns the response.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Real-World Example: Stripe</h2>
      <p>
        Stripe is famous for its robust implementation of idempotency. When you create a charge, 
        you pass an <code>idempotency_key</code>. If the request fails halfway through, you can 
        safely retry with the same key knowing Stripe won't create a second charge.
      </p>

      <h2>Key Benefits</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Fault Tolerance:</strong> Clients can safely retry failed network requests.</li>
        <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> Prevents duplicate records and inconsistent states.</li>
        <li><strong>User Experience:</strong> No "Double Charge" or "Duplicate Post" errors.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>
        Idempotency is often overlooked until something goes wrong. If you are building APIs 
        that handle sensitive data—especially payments or inventory—idempotency is not a 
        luxury; it is a requirement. By implementing unique request keys and caching 
        responses, you build systems that are predictable, safe, and truly reliable.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

